title: For Sale:  SIG SG 551 Rifle – 1 of 250! SWISS LOWER! LNIB!
postcontent:
You are bidding on a Limited Edition Sig Sauer Sig SG551 originally brought to you exclusively by West Coast Armory. Completely assembled by Sig Sauer, this rifle is one of just 250 built from new-in-box Swiss SIG SG 551 rifles that were stuck in customs before WCA and SigSauer rescued them and built these limited edition collector's pieces. Learn more at www.sig551.com.

Do not confuse this Sig Sauer SG551 with the latest release by Sig Sauer, the 551-A1. This rifle is comprised of a Swiss made lower with matching serial numbers on the upper and lower receivers. This is truly a collector's piece that has the capability of being your everyday rifle as well. This fine rifle features an adjustable gas operated piston driven long stroke system that is considered the most reliable system made today; it is very accurate and fires from a closed bolt. The trigger mechanism has an ambidextrous safety and fire selector switch that has four settings: "S"—safe, "1"—single fire, "3"—3 round burst and "20"—fully automatic fire. Note: this rifle is semi-automatic and has a factory guard installed that prohibits the selector from moving to the burst or full-auto positions. The trigger is enclosed in a pivoting trigger guard which can be folded down to the left or right side allowing for unhindered operation with winter gloves.

LIKE NEW IN BOX: SG 551 semi-automatic 5.56 x 45mm NATO Rifle with a 16-inch barrel and side-folding stock. Overall length is 24-inches with the stock folded and 32.5-inches with the stock extended. Weight: 7.5 pounds. Length of pull: 13.4 inches. Beautiful black Swiss Style furniture. This particular rifle is like new-in-box and has been fired less than 50 rounds to verify function. title: For Sale:  Precision Small Arms Pocket Pistol .25 ACP Polished Blued Finish
postcontent:
This PSA is in Like New condition, just a few rounds fired through it. Includes everything from the factory new.

The makers of the American made "Baby Browning" pistol trade here in the USA under the brand name Precision Small Arms and the pistol is known as the "PSA-25". Outside of the USA the pistol carries the Fabrique Nationale name on the slide and sports Browning labeled grips. The "Baby Browning" pistol has been in production since the early 1930's and has spawned many imitators throughout the world. It is an exquisite firearm highly prized for its sleek lines, beautiful finish, precision craftsmanship, diminutive size and exceptional close range accuracy. When utilized with modern high-velocity ammunition, the Pistol can achieve the effectiveness of a .380. It should not be under-estimated with regard to lethality.
PSA has been manufacturing this timeless classic since 1984, most recently in the fresh Rocky Mountain air of Aspen, Colorado. In a small workshop, they use state-of-the-art, computer numeric controlled machinery supported by in-process dimensional control inspection technology to assure near perfection of all machined parts. After machining, each Pistol is hand fitted, tested and inspected in an effort to provide a flawless product for a highly discriminating clientele.
The "Baby Browning" pistol is a single action, semi-automatic, self-loading, blow-back mechanism manufactured from all steel alloy components (with the exception of the "Featherweight" version which utilizes a 7075 forged aluminum receiver). It is striker fired and has a smooth faced, single stage draw bar trigger with pull weight of 5.25 lbs. The Pistol can hold seven rounds: six in its magazine and one chambered.

Specifications

.25 ACP caliber

title: For Sale:  M1 Carbine
postcontent:
I have my dads 45, 38, and M1 carbine. I have his discharge papers showing the 45 and 38 checked out to him. The 45 and M1 carbine come with extra stuff. The 38 is a S&W made for the government in October of 1943. I am selling all three for $2000, no trades.
The 45 is a Remington Rand. According to the serial no 1016319 and what I have been told it is a sand cast model. All the items that are in the picture with it were brought home at the same time except for the pair of grips on it,camo holster and the extended clip. The US holster is the one my Dad got with the gun. The rest was all my Dads personal gear issue to him. The three clips are the original clips that came with the gun.
The S&W 38 serial no is V424979 and according to that it was shipped in October of 1943. Guns without a top strap marking usually shipped per contracts with the Defense Supplies Corporation or the U.S. Maritime Commission. This would make sense as my Dad picked up the Mine Sweeper from Puget Sound Naval Shipyard Washington around Christmas 1943. I know this because he shipped out on the Mine Sweeper right after he married my Mom in Puget Sound. He only had a week before he shipped out.
The M1 Carbine was issue to him at the same time. It is an Inland Division of General Motors serial no 46458. The receiver was made somewhere between October, 1941 - April, 1942. The barrel is marked 5-43. The carbine was usually assembled and tested within two or three months after the barrel date. This is a very early one and is quite rare in this shape.
Do your homework on these guns. You will see that I am selling them below market value. Just the carbine alone is worth around $2000 in the condition it’s in. Go here to check: http://www.scott-duff.com click on M1 Carbine at the bottom of the page or anyone of the many internet listings.

The SureFire high-capacity magazine for 5.56x45 mm (.223 Remington) ammunition, also available in a 100-round version, is compatible with M4/M16/AR-15 variants and other firearms that accept standard STANAG 4179 magazines. Constructed from Mil-Spec hard-anodized aluminum, they feed smoothly and reliably due to optimal geometry, non-binding coil springs, and ingenious nesting polymer followers. The long-lasting springs are cadmium coated for low friction and excellent corrosion resistance. Magazines require no lubricants and can be easily disassembled without tools for cleaning. SureFire High capacity magazines provide distinct tactical advantages: increased initial firepower in ambush situations; fewer reloads overall, which means less downtime and target distraction in a firefight; fast and easy magazine insertion, even with a closed bolt; less bulk compared to drum mags, enabling a normal weapon grip. The 60-round magazine—slightly thinner than two 30-round magazines clipped together and about the same overall length—fits in most dual magazine pouches, eliminating special carry pouches required for drum magazines. Features: Compatible with all weapons that accept standard STANAG 4179 compliant magazines Reliable functioning due to mechanical simplicity and high-quality non-binding coil springs—no lubricants required Long-lasting springs are cadmium coated for low friction and excellent corrosion resistance Easily seated in weapon with bolt forward May be kept fully loaded for extended periods without spring fatigue Only 1.66" thick, less than two 30-round magazines clipped together 60-round magazine is approximately same length as two 30-round magazines clipped together 60-round magazine fits in most dual-mag pouches
